               <p>GEORGE MERITT. I am a <rs id="t18310217-245-viclabel1435" type="occupation">labourer</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310217-245-victim2255 t18310217-245-viclabel1435"></join>, and live at <placeName id="t18310217-245-crimeloc1436">Finchley</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18310217-245-crimeloc1436" type="placeName" value="Finchley"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18310217-245-crimeloc1436" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310217-245-off1433 t18310217-245-crimeloc1436"></join>. On the 19th of February I saw the prisoner at Lord Mansfield's-wood, with some wood; I asked if he wanted a job; he said, Yes - I asked if he could do ditching - he said a little, but he had no spade, nor money to buy one; he came to work on Saturday morning, but it being wet, he was late, and I told him he must come earlier in future - I borrowed a spade, and set him to work - it was breakfast time; he said he had no money nor breakfast - I said, "Well, sixpence is no object - I have a quartern loaf at home, and you shall have half of it;" I went home, returned in twenty minutes, and the spade I had lent him was stuck in the ground, but my spade was gone, and him also - I went and told a Policeman, and he was taken; it was my master's spade, but I am answerable for it.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310217-245-person2256">
